{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A request whose signature does not match its body is rejected with a 401 response; the body is not forwarded.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure commonly appears at the real HTTP boundary where raw bytes, headers, and body parsing interact. A unit/integration fake can miss raw-body/signature mismatches caused by framework middleware order or transport encoding. Rejected higher levels: not Agentic/Workflow because behavior text is purely HMAC/HTTP with no AI step.","test_description":"Run the Node service with its real HTTP stack, send a webhook over HTTP with intentionally mismatched `X-Signature-256` vs raw payload bytes, assert `401`, and assert no queue write occurred.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.72,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"An event is written to the persistent queue before the HTTP 200 acknowledgment is returned to the sender.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is an ordering/handoff failure between handler and queue modules. It needs real module wiring plus real persistence semantics, but not OS/network effects beyond in-process app + local persistence. Rejected higher levels: System disqualified because behavior text does not require real network timing path, only write-before-ack ordering; Agentic/Workflow disqualified (no model decisions).","test_description":"With the real handler + real persistent queue implementation (e.g., local DB/filesystem), trigger a valid request and instrument timestamps/events to assert queue commit completes before `200` is emitted.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.28,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The handler returns the HTTP response without waiting for downstream processing of the event to finish.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure is asynchronous coupling between enqueue/ack path and downstream worker path across modules. A unit test of one function is too narrow, but real OS/network/subprocess behavior is not required to expose it. Rejected higher levels: System disqualified because behavior only requires non-blocking orchestration, not real network conditions; Agentic/Workflow disqualified (no AI steps).","test_description":"Wire real handler + queue + downstream processor module where processor intentionally sleeps; send valid event and assert response returns before processor completion while event still gets processed later.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The response arrives within 3 seconds wall-clock time even when downstream processing of earlier events is slow and concurrent.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is explicitly a wall-clock latency/concurrency requirement under load-like conditions. In-process mocks often hide event-loop contention, scheduling, socket/backpressure, and real timing behavior. Rejected higher levels: Agentic/Workflow disqualified because behavior text is concurrency/latency only, with no AI model decisions.","test_description":"Start the service, create concurrent traffic with earlier events tied to slow downstream processing, and measure end-to-end HTTP response latency for new requests; assert responses stay under 3 seconds wall-clock.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.76,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"An event whose ID was already received is not written to the queue a second time.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Idempotency here is a cross-module state/persistence behavior (handler + dedup storage/queue). Unit